ooks are\r\u001b[5d# run.  Advanced users may wish to specify all system modules\r\u001b[6d# in this array.  For instance:\r\u001b[7d#     MODULES=(usbhid xhci_hcd)\r\u001b[8dMODULES=()\r\u001b[10d# BINARIES\r\u001b[11d# This setting includes any additional binaries a given user may\r\u001b[12d# wish into the CPIO image.  This is run last, so it may be used to\r\u001b[13d# override the actual binaries included by a given hook\r\u001b[14d# BINARIES are dependency parsed, so you may safely ignore libraries\r\u001b[15dBINARIES=()\r\u001b[17d# FILES\r\u001b[18d# This setting is similar to BINARIES above, however, files are added\r\u001b[19d# as-is and are not parsed in any way.  This is useful for config files.\r\u001b[20dFILES=()\r\u001b[22d# HOOKS\r\u001b[23d# This is the most important setting in this file.  The HOOKS control the\r\u001b[24d# modules and scripts added to the image, and what happens at boot time.\r\u001b[25d# Order is important, and it is recommended that you do not change the\r\u001b[26d# order in which HOOKS are added.  Run 'mkinitcpio -H <hook name>' for\r\u001b[27d# help on a given hook.\r\u001b[28d# 'base' is _required_ unless you know precisely what you are doing.\r\u001b[29d# 'udev' is _required_ in order to automatically load modules\r\u001b[30d# 'filesystems' is _required_ unless you specify your fs modules in MODULES\r\u001b[31d# Examples:\r\u001b[32d##   This setup specifies all modules in the MODULES setting above.\r\u001b[33d##   No RAID, lvm2, or encrypted root is needed.\r\u001b[34d#    HOOKS=(base)\r\u001b[35d#\u001b[36d\b##   This setup will autodetect all modules for your system and should\r\u001b[37d##   work as a sane default\r\u001b[38d#    HOOKS=(base udev autodetect microcode modconf block filesystems fsck)\r\u001b[39d#\u001b[40d\b##   This setup will generate a 'full' image which supports most systems.\r\u001b[41d##   No autodetection is done.\r\u001b[42d#    HOOKS=(base udev microcode modconf block filesystems fsck)\r\u001b[43d#\u001b[44d\b##   This setup assembles a mdadm array with an encrypted root file system.\r\u001b[45d##   Note: See 'mkinitcpio -H mdadm_udev' for more information on RAID devices.\r\u001b[46d#    HOOKS=(base udev microcode modconf keyboard keymap consolefont block mdadm_udev encrypt filesystems fsck)\r\u001b[47d#\u001b[48d\b##   This setup loads an lvm2 volume group.\r\u001b[49d#    HOOKS=(base udev microcode modconf block lvm2 filesystems fsck)\r\u001b[50d#\u001b[51d\b##   This will create a systemd based initramfs which loads an encrypted root filesystem.\r\u001b[52d#    HOOKS=(base systemd autodetect microcode modconf kms keyboard sd-vconsole block sd-encrypt filesystems fsck)\r\u001b[53d#\u001b[54d\b##   NOTE: If you have /usr on a separate partition, you MUST include the\r\u001b[55d#    usr and fsck hooks.\r\u001b[56dHOOKS=(base systemd autodetect microcode modconf kms keyboard sd-vconsole block lvm2 sd-encrpt filesystems fsck)\r\u001b[58d# COMPRESSION\r\u001b[59d# Use this to compress the initramfs image. By default, zstd compression\r\u001b[60d# is used for Linux ≥ 5.9 and gzip compression is used for Linux < 5.9.\r\u001b["]
[0.000, "o", "61d# Use 'cat' to create an uncompressed image.\r\u001b[62d#COMPRESSION=\"zstd\"\r\u001b[63d#COMPRESSION=\"gzip\"\r\u001b[64d#COMPRESSION=\"bzip2\"\r\u001b[2d\u001b[?25h\u001b[?0c"]
